---
dops: v1
kind: tool

meta:
  name: systemd
  version: 1.0.0
  description: "Generate systemd service unit files"
  author: dojops
  license: MIT
  tags: [systemd, service, daemon, linux, init]

input:
  fields:
    serviceName:
      type: string
      required: true
      description: "Name of the systemd service (e.g. 'my-app')"
      pattern: "^[a-z][a-z0-9-]*$"
    execStart:
      type: string
      required: true
      description: "Command to start the service"
    user:
      type: string
      default: "root"
    workingDirectory:
      type: string
      description: "Working directory for the service"
    description:
      type: string
      default: "Custom service"
    outputPath:
      type: string
      required: true
      description: "Directory to write the unit file to"
    environment:
      type: string

output:
  type: object
  required: [content]
  properties:
    content:
      type: string
      description: "Complete systemd unit file content as INI-format text"

files:
  - path: "{outputPath}/{serviceName}.service"
    format: raw
    source: llm
    dataPath: content

detection:
  paths: ["{serviceName}.service", "*.service", "/etc/systemd/system/{serviceName}.service"]
  updateMode: true

verification:
  structural:
    - path: "content"
      required: true
      type: string
      message: "Service unit content is required"

  binary:
    command: "systemd-analyze verify service.service"
    parser: systemd-analyze
    timeout: 30000
    cwd: output

permissions:
  filesystem: write
  child_process: required
  network: none

scope:
  write: ["{outputPath}/{serviceName}.service"]

risk:
  level: MEDIUM
  rationale: "Service unit changes affect system processes"

execution:
  mode: generate
  deterministic: false
  idempotent: true

update:
  strategy: replace
  inputSource: file
  injectAs: existingContent
---
# Systemd

## Prompt

You are a Linux systems expert. Generate a systemd service unit file as text.

You MUST respond with a JSON object containing a "content" field with the complete systemd unit file as a string.

The unit file should include:
- [Unit] section with Description and After directives
- [Service] section with ExecStart, User, WorkingDirectory, Restart policy
- [Install] section with WantedBy directive
- Environment variables if needed
- Security hardening directives

Response format:
{
  "content": "[Unit]\nDescription=My Application Service\nAfter=network.target\n\n[Service]\nType=simple\nUser=appuser\nWorkingDirectory=/opt/myapp\nExecStart=/usr/bin/node /opt/myapp/index.js\nRestart=on-failure\nRestartSec=5\nEnvironment=NODE_ENV=production\n\n[Install]\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\n"
}

IMPORTANT:
- "content" must contain the COMPLETE unit file as a string
- Include [Unit], [Service], and [Install] sections
- Use Restart=on-failure or Restart=always
- Include security directives (NoNewPrivileges, ProtectSystem)
- Respond with valid JSON only, no markdown

## Update Prompt

You are a Linux systems expert. Update the existing systemd unit file.
Preserve existing settings. Only add/modify what is requested.

--- EXISTING CONFIGURATION ---
{existingContent}
--- END EXISTING CONFIGURATION ---

Respond with a JSON object containing a "content" field with the complete updated unit file.

IMPORTANT:
- Preserve existing directives unless explicitly asked to change them
- Maintain existing security settings
- Respond with valid JSON only, no markdown

## Examples

Given: "Systemd service for a Node.js app running on port 3000"

```json
{
  "content": "[Unit]\nDescription=Node.js Application\nAfter=network.target\nWants=network-online.target\n\n[Service]\nType=simple\nUser=nodeapp\nGroup=nodeapp\nWorkingDirectory=/opt/nodeapp\nExecStart=/usr/bin/node /opt/nodeapp/server.js\nRestart=on-failure\nRestartSec=10\nStandardOutput=journal\nStandardError=journal\nSyslogIdentifier=nodeapp\nEnvironment=NODE_ENV=production\nEnvironment=PORT=3000\n\n# Security hardening\nNoNewPrivileges=true\nProtectSystem=strict\nProtectHome=true\nReadWritePaths=/opt/nodeapp/data\nPrivateTmp=true\n\n[Install]\nWantedBy=multi-user.target\n"
}
```

## Constraints

- Always include [Unit], [Service], and [Install] sections
- Use Restart=on-failure with RestartSec
- Include security hardening directives
- Use journal for logging (StandardOutput/StandardError)
- Run as non-root user when possible
- No hardcoded secrets in Environment directives

## Keywords

systemd, service, unit, daemon, linux, systemctl, init,
enable, start, stop, restart, journal, socket
